import{_ as o,o as t,c as r,ag as i}from"./chunks/framework.DwYrYzXn.js";const g=JSON.parse('{"title":"Repository Architecture: Monorepos vs. Git Submodules","description":"","frontmatter":{},"headers":[],"relativePath":"plan/repository-architecture.md","filePath":"plan/repository-architecture.md"}'),n={name:"plan/repository-architecture.md"};function a(s,e,l,c,d,p){return t(),r("div",null,[...e[0]||(e[0]=[i('<h1 id="repository-architecture-monorepos-vs-git-submodules" tabindex="-1">Repository Architecture: Monorepos vs. Git Submodules <a class="header-anchor" href="#repository-architecture-monorepos-vs-git-submodules" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Repository Architecture: Monorepos vs. Git Submodules&quot;">​</a></h1><p>This document outlines the architectural trade-offs between managing the Tempo ecosystem as a unified Monorepo (via NPM Workspaces) versus separating it into independent repositories linked via Git Submodules.</p><h2 id="_1-security-and-isolation-the-biggest-win" tabindex="-1">1. Security and Isolation (The Biggest Win) <a class="header-anchor" href="#_1-security-and-isolation-the-biggest-win" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;1. Security and Isolation (The Biggest Win)&quot;">​</a></h2><p>If the primary goal is to allow third-party developers or contractors to work on specific plugins <strong>without exposing the proprietary <code>magma</code> core</strong>, Git Submodules (or entirely separate repositories) are practically required.</p><ul><li><strong>The Value:</strong> A monorepo is all-or-nothing. If a developer clones <code>magma</code>, they have the whole tree. If you spin <code>tempo-plugin-ticker</code> out into its own repository and link it via a submodule, you can grant granular GitHub RBAC (Role-Based Access Control) to just that plugin.</li><li><strong>The Verdict:</strong> If strict IP isolation is a business requirement for external developers, submodules (or separate repos) will absolutely solve this.</li></ul><h2 id="_2-versioning-and-release-tracking" tabindex="-1">2. Versioning and Release Tracking <a class="header-anchor" href="#_2-versioning-and-release-tracking" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;2. Versioning and Release Tracking&quot;">​</a></h2><p>The ecosystem has varying release cadences, meaning version numbers do not track consistently across plugins.</p><ul><li><strong>The Submodule Approach:</strong> Submodules give each plugin its own isolated Git history, tags, and releases. A plugin can be at <code>v1.2.0</code> while the core is at <code>v3.0.0</code>.</li><li><strong>The Monorepo Alternative:</strong> You actually <strong>do not</strong> need submodules to solve independent versioning. Modern monorepo tooling like <a href="https://github.com/changesets/changesets" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Changesets</a> or Lerna are specifically designed to handle independent versioning across workspaces in a single Git repository. They automatically track which workspaces changed and bump/tag their versions independently.</li></ul><h2 id="_3-the-submodule-tax-developer-experience" tabindex="-1">3. The &quot;Submodule Tax&quot; (Developer Experience) <a class="header-anchor" href="#_3-the-submodule-tax-developer-experience" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;3. The &quot;Submodule Tax&quot; (Developer Experience)&quot;">​</a></h2><p>While submodules solve isolation, they introduce notorious Developer Experience (DX) friction:</p><ul><li><strong>Detached HEADs:</strong> Developers constantly forget to run <code>git submodule update</code>, leading to misaligned commits and build failures.</li><li><strong>Cross-Boundary Refactoring:</strong> In a monorepo, changing an interface in the core instantly highlights breaking changes across all plugins in the IDE. With submodules, cross-repo refactoring becomes a multi-PR chore (update core -&gt; publish/push -&gt; update plugin -&gt; fix -&gt; push).</li><li><strong>CI/CD Complexity:</strong> CI pipelines now have to manage SSH keys and deployment tokens to clone private submodules during the build process.</li></ul><h2 id="recommended-hybrid-strategy" tabindex="-1">Recommended Hybrid Strategy <a class="header-anchor" href="#recommended-hybrid-strategy" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Recommended Hybrid Strategy&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Instead of converting the <em>entire</em> monorepo to submodules, a Hybrid Strategy offers the best balance of velocity and security:</p><ol><li><strong>Keep First-Party Code in the Monorepo:</strong> Keep the <code>magma</code> core, the core licensing engine, and any highly-sensitive proprietary premium plugins in the standard workspace monorepo. Use a tool like <strong>Changesets</strong> to handle independent versioning. This preserves lightning-fast DX and atomic cross-repo refactoring.</li><li><strong>Use Separate Repos for External Developers:</strong> When onboarding external developers, create a completely separate, standalone repository for their plugin (e.g., <code>tempo-plugin-community</code>).</li><li><strong>Treat Core as a Dependency:</strong> External developers shouldn&#39;t need the core source code to build a plugin. They should just install the <code>@magmacomputing/tempo</code> package via NPM (or a private registry) as a <code>peerDependency</code>. They build, test, and publish their plugin in total isolation.</li></ol>',14)])])}const h=o(n,[["render",a]]);export{g as __pageData,h as default};
